SIMPLE: plague
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Plague
<hw>Plague</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>plaga</ets> a
blow, stroke, plague; akin to Gr. <?/, fr. <?/ to strike; cf. L.
<ets>plangere</ets> to strike, beat. Cf. <er>Plaint</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>That which smites, wounds, or troubles; a blow; a
calamity; any afflictive evil or torment; a great trail or
vexation.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And men blasphemed God for the <qex>plague</qex> of hail.</q>
<rj><qau>Wyclif.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The different <qex>plague</qex> of each calamity.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>An acute malignant contagious
fever, that often prevails in Egypt, Syria, and Turkey, and has at times
visited the large cities of Europe with frightful mortality; hence, any
pestilence; <as>as, the great London <ex>plague</ex></as>.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧A <xex>plague</xex> upon the people fell.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Tennyson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Cattle plague</b></col>. <cd>See
<er>Rinderpest</er>.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Plague mark</b></col>,
<col><b>Plague spot</b></col></mcol>, <cd>a spot or mark of the plague;
hence, a token of something incurable.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Plague</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Plague
<hw>Plague</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Plagued</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Plaguing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To infest or afflict
with disease, calamity, or natural evil of any kind.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thus were they <qex>plagued</qex>⟦br⟧
And worn with famine.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Fig.: To vex; to tease; to harass.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She will <qex>plague</qex> the man that loves her most.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To vex; torment; distress; afflict; harass;
annoy; tease; tantalize; trouble; molest; embarrass; perplex.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Plagueful</ent>⟦br⟧
